What Happens When Not Embarrassingly Parallel?

Think of the difference between linear and quadratic equations in algebra:
\(3x - 1 = 0\) is ‚Äúembarrassingly‚Äù solvable, on its own: you can solve it directly, by adding 3 to both sides \(\implies x = \frac{1}{3}\). Same for \(2x + 3 = 0 \implies x = -\frac{3}{2}\)
Now consider \(6x^2 + 7x - 3 = 0\): Harder to solve ‚Äúdirectly‚Äù, so your instinct might be to turn to the laborious quadratic equation:

\[
\begin{align*}
x = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} = \frac{-7 \pm \sqrt{49 - 4(6)(-3)}}{2(6)} = \frac{-7 \pm 11}{12} = \left\{\frac{1}{3},-\frac{3}{2}\right\}
\end{align*}
\]

And yet, \(6x^2 + 7x - 3 = (3x - 1)(2x + 3)\), meaning that we could have split the problem into two ‚Äúembarrassingly‚Äù solvable pieces, then multiplied to get result!

